  "signature": "ed25519:b2e4a6c8d0f1e3a5b7c9d2f4a6e8c0b2d4f6a8e0c2b4d6f8a0e2c4b6d8f0a2c4",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-sqa",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "FEA software must hold current FDA-recognized validation documentation and be operated under a documented quality management system. Version control and audit trail required for all simulation inputs and outputs."
      },
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 was used as the primary solver. The software is operated under a 21 CFR Part 820-compliant QMS maintained by DePuy Synthes. Version control was enforced via Git-based repository with signed commits for all input decks, material property files, and post-processing scripts. Ansys holds current FDA-recognized validation documentation (Ansys Structural Mechanics Verification Manual). An independent software qualification test suite covering linear elastic, contact, and large-deformation regimes was executed at study initiation and passed all benchmarks. Audit trail confirms no unauthorized modifications between validation runs. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects documented QMS coverage, independent benchmark testing, and traceability of all simulation artifacts."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ncv",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Code verification must demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations through comparison to analytical solutions or established benchmarks for the relevant physics (structural mechanics, contact, large deformation)."
      },
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed using three benchmark problems representative of the COU physics: (1) Euler-Bernoulli beam bending with known analytical solution — FEA error < 0.1%; (2) Hertzian contact between cylindrical surfaces — FEA contact pressure within 0.8% of analytical; (3) large-deformation cantilever beam (Bathe benchmark) — FEA tip displacement within 0.5% of reference solution. All benchmarks were documented in a code verification report reviewed and approved by the study lead engineer. The ASME V&V 10 hierarchy was followed, with manufactured solution verification for the nonlinear solver confirming spatial convergence rates consistent with second-order accuracy. Gradation 3 achieved through systematic benchmark coverage spanning all relevant physics modes."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-discretization",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Discretization error must be quantified through systematic mesh refinement study. Discretization error contribution to total uncertainty must be demonstrably smaller than experimental variability. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) or equivalent must be reported for each QoI."
      },
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted using mesh refinement ratios of 1.5 between successive levels. Coarse mesh: 47,832 elements; medium mesh: 108,441 elements; fine mesh: 244,892 elements. Richardson extrapolation was applied to estimate the exact solution for each QoI. GCI values: stiffness GCI = 0.31%, yield force GCI = 0.47%, force at 40 mm GCI = 0.52%. All GCI values are well below the 2% threshold established in the analysis plan. The fine mesh was selected for all production runs. Mesh quality metrics (Jacobian ratio > 0.7, aspect ratio < 5 for all elements in high-stress regions) confirmed. Contact zone mesh density was independently verified against Hertzian contact benchmark results. Discretization error contribution is negligible relative to material property uncertainty, confirming Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-solver",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Iterative solver convergence must be demonstrated for all nonlinear solution steps. Force and displacement residual norms must fall below specified tolerances. Time/load-step sensitivity must be assessed."
      },
      "rationale": "The nonlinear Newton-Raphson solver was employed with force residual tolerance of 1e-4 and displacement residual tolerance of 1e-5. All 11 simulation cases converged within 15 load increments with no divergence events. Residual histories were logged and reviewed; all force residuals fell below 1e-4 by iteration 8 in the most challenging (post-yield) load steps. A load-step sensitivity study using half the reference step size showed QoI changes of less than 0.2% for all outputs, confirming step-size independence. Direct sparse solver (PARDISO) was used for the linear sub-problem, eliminating iterative linear solver error. Gradation 2 reflects documented convergence monitoring and load-step independence verification, consistent with the required level for this model risk tier."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-use-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Evidence that model setup, boundary condition application, and post-processing were performed correctly and consistently. Independent review or cross-check of simulation inputs required."
      },
      "rationale": "All simulation input decks were independently reviewed by a second qualified FEA engineer not involved in model construction. A structured checklist covering geometry import, material assignment, contact definitions, boundary condition application, and load application was completed for each of the 11 cases. Discrepancies identified during review (two instances of incorrect friction coefficient assignment in initial setup) were corrected prior to production runs, and corrected inputs were re-reviewed and signed off. Post-processing scripts were validated against hand calculations for a representative subset of results. The cross-organizational nature of the ensemble (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes teams) provided additional independent verification of modeling decisions. Gradation 3 reflects systematic independent review with documented correction and re-verification cycle."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "The mathematical model (constitutive laws, contact formulation, geometric assumptions) must be justified for the COU physics. Model form uncertainty must be characterized and shown not to dominate total prediction uncertainty."
      },
      "rationale": "The model employs a bilinear isotropic hardening constitutive model for Ti-6Al-4V, calibrated against coupon tensile test data (n=6 coupons per batch). The UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate is modeled as linear elastic, consistent with the small strains observed in the surrogate during F1717 testing. Augmented Lagrangian contact formulation is used for screw-rod and screw-block interfaces, with friction coefficients informed by tribology literature and sensitivity-tested over the range 0.1 to 0.3. Geometric nonlinearity (large deformation) is activated, appropriate for the 40 mm displacement range. Model form uncertainty was assessed through comparison of three independently constructed model variants (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes); inter-model QoI spread was less than 3% for all outputs, bounding model form uncertainty. Gradation 3 reflects justified constitutive modeling, contact formulation selection, and quantified inter-model spread."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "All model inputs (material properties, geometry, boundary conditions) must be traceable to measured data or justified assumptions. Input uncertainty distributions must be characterized and propagated."
      },
      "rationale": "Material properties for Ti-6Al-4V (elastic modulus, yield strength, tangent modulus) were measured from 18 coupon specimens machined from the same bar stock as the test constructs, providing lot-specific property distributions. Geometric inputs were derived from CMM measurements of actual test constructs (n=5 constructs measured), with dimensional uncertainty characterized as normal distributions with measured standard deviations. UHMWPE surrogate elastic modulus was taken from manufacturer datasheet with a stated tolerance of plus or minus 5%, treated as uniform distribution. Boundary condition uncertainty (grip compliance, alignment) was assessed through sensitivity analysis. All input distributions were documented in a traceable input uncertainty register linked to the simulation dataset. Monte Carlo propagation used 10,000 samples. Gradation 3 reflects lot-specific material characterization, CMM-based geometry inputs, and fully documented uncertainty propagation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-test-samples",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Test samples must be representative of the device population. Sample size must be sufficient to characterize experimental variability. Traceability of samples to production processes must be documented."
      },
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (n=6 at Lab 1, n=5 at Lab 2). All constructs were assembled from production-representative components manufactured under the same process controls as commercial devices, with full lot traceability documented. CMM inspection confirmed dimensional conformance to drawing tolerances for all 11 constructs. Inter-laboratory variability was assessed; coefficient of variation for stiffness was 4.2% within Lab 1 and 3.8% within Lab 2, with no statistically significant inter-laboratory bias detected (Welch t-test, p=0.34 for stiffness). The sample size of 11 provides adequate power to detect a 10% QoI difference at 80% power given the observed variability. Gradation 3 reflects production-representative samples, full lot traceability, CMM verification, and inter-laboratory consistency assessment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Test conditions must replicate the ASTM F1717 protocol. Environmental conditions, loading rates, and fixture configurations must be documented and shown to be consistent with the FEA boundary conditions. Deviations from standard conditions must be assessed for impact on QoIs."
      },
      "rationale": "All testing was conducted in strict accordance with ASTM F1717-15 under ambient laboratory conditions (23 plus or minus 2 degrees C, 50 plus or minus 10% RH) as specified in the standard. Load was applied at 25 mm/min displacement rate consistent with quasi-static assumption in the FEA. Fixture compliance was measured for both test frames and incorporated into the FEA boundary conditions as a linear spring element with stiffness derived from compliance calibration data. Load cell calibration certificates (NIST-traceable) were current for both laboratories at time of testing. The single test condition (ambient, quasi-static) is acknowledged as a limitation; however, the ASTM F1717 standard specifies this condition as the regulatory benchmark, and the FEA is explicitly scoped to this condition. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that temperature variation within the specified range has less than 0.5% effect on predicted QoIs. Gradation 3 reflects full protocol compliance, documented fixture compliance correction, and quantified sensitivity to environmental variation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-equivalency",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "FEA input parameters must be demonstrably equivalent to the physical test parameters. Material properties, geometry, and boundary conditions used in the model must correspond to measured values from the actual test specimens and conditions."
      },
      "rationale": "A formal equivalency mapping was constructed documenting each FEA input parameter alongside its experimental counterpart and the evidence for equivalency. Material properties in the FEA were set to the measured lot-specific mean values from coupon testing of the same bar stock. Geometric parameters were set to the CMM-measured mean dimensions of the 11 test constructs, with construct-specific geometry sensitivity assessed by running FEA with the measured dimensional extremes. Boundary conditions (grip separation, fixture stiffness) were set to values measured during test frame characterization. The UHMWPE surrogate modulus was matched to the manufacturer-certified value for the specific lot used in testing. No surrogate or assumed inputs were used where measured values were available. Gradation 3 reflects comprehensive parameter-by-parameter equivalency documentation with measurement traceability for all inputs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval must be less than 1.96 for each QoI. Percentage difference between FEA mean prediction and experimental mean must be less than 10% for each QoI. Comparison must account for both simulation and experimental uncertainty."
      },
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed for all three QoIs using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval, where E is the absolute difference between FEA prediction and experimental mean, and uval is the combined validation uncertainty (root-sum-square of simulation uncertainty and experimental uncertainty). Results: stiffness E/uval = 0.43 (1.7% difference), yield force E/uval = 0.31 (1.2% difference), force at 40 mm E/uval = 0.62 (2.5% difference). All three QoIs satisfy both the E/uval < 1.96 criterion and the 10% difference criterion with substantial margin. Graphical comparison of force-displacement curves shows good agreement across the full loading range. Inter-laboratory consistency was confirmed; predictions are within the experimental variability band for both laboratories. Gradation 3 reflects rigorous quantitative comparison with uncertainty decomposition and graphical validation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-qoi-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "The QoIs used in validation (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) must be directly relevant to the clinical and regulatory decision. The link between QoIs and device performance must be documented."
      },
      "rationale": "The three QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are directly specified in ASTM F1717 as the primary performance metrics for spinal fixation construct evaluation and are the quantities cited in FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions. Construct stiffness is mechanically relevant to load sharing with the fusion mass; yield force characterizes the onset of permanent deformation under physiological loading; force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield energy absorption relevant to catastrophic failure scenarios. The regulatory relevance of each QoI was documented in a QoI justification memo reviewed by the clinical and regulatory affairs team. No surrogate or derived QoIs are used; all three are directly measurable from the F1717 test and directly predictable from the FEA. Gradation 3 reflects explicit regulatory linkage, clinical justification, and direct measurability of all QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-validation-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "The validation activities must be relevant to the COU in terms of geometry, material, loading, and boundary conditions. The degree of similarity between the validation scenario and the intended use scenario must be documented and justified."
      },
      "rationale": "The validation activity (ASTM F1717 bench testing of non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs) is directly identical to the COU — the FEA model is validated on the exact device design, material lot, and test protocol that constitutes the regulatory submission basis. There is no extrapolation required between the validation scenario and the COU: the geometry is production-representative (verified by CMM), the material is from the same lot as the submission device, the loading protocol is the regulatory standard, and the boundary conditions replicate the test setup. The two-laboratory design increases confidence that results are not laboratory-specific. The only acknowledged gap between validation and full clinical use is that in vivo loading is more complex than F1717; however, the regulatory framework explicitly accepts F1717 as the relevant benchmark for this device class, and the model is scoped to the F1717 prediction task only. Gradation 3 reflects direct correspondence between validation scenario and COU with no unmitigated gaps within the defined model scope."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw compression-bending FEA) is accepted based on the following structured evidence: (1) All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed, and achievedLevel meets or exceeds requiredLevel for every factor. (2) All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) satisfy the pre-established quantitative acceptance criteria: percentage differences of 1.7%, 1.2%, and 2.5% respectively (all below the 10% bound), and E/uval values of 0.43, 0.31, and 0.62 respectively (all well below the 1.96 threshold). (3) The uncertainty quantification is comprehensive, incorporating lot-specific material property variability, CMM-measured geometric uncertainty, boundary condition uncertainty, and model form uncertainty from the three-model ensemble; total simulation uncertainty is dominated by material property variability rather than numerical or model form error. (4) The provenance chain is complete: all simulation inputs are traceable to measured data, all experimental data has documented calibration and traceability, and all model artifacts are under version control with independent review. (5) The validation scenario is directly relevant to the COU with no unmitigated scope gaps within the defined model boundaries. (6) The two-laboratory experimental design with N=11 constructs provides adequate statistical power and confirms absence of inter-laboratory bias. The assessment team concludes that the FEA modeling framework has demonstrated sufficient credibility for use in the regulatory submission for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending loading, consistent with the Medium assurance level required for a Model Risk Level 3, Class II device with Medium model influence and Medium decision consequence.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
